T1  - ILLIQUIDITY COMPONENT OF CREDIT RISK – THE 2015 LAWRENCE R. KLEIN LECTURE
AU  - Morris, Stephen
AU  - Shin, Hyun Song
Y1  - 2016/11/01
PY  - 2016
DA  - 2016/11/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12192
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
JA  - International Economic Review
SP  - 1135
EP  - 1148
VL  - 57
IS  - 4
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12192
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - We provide a theoretical decomposition of bank credit risk into insolvency risk and illiquidity risk, defining illiquidity risk to be the counterfactual probability of failure due to a run when the bank would have survived in the absence of a run. We show that illiquidity risk is (i) decreasing in the ?liquidity ratio??the ratio of realizable cash on the balance sheet to short-term liabilities; (ii) decreasing in the excess return of debt; and (iii) increasing in the solvency uncertainty?a measure of the variance of the asset portfolio.
ER  - 

